Now we will discuss only the recommendations that Pol.nat gives for the best approaches to make the most effective decisions.

48:53.000 --> 49:09.000
He says that you need to learn to use, to look for the best approaches at each stage of the process of decision-making.

49:10.000 --> 49:19.000
That is, it is, first of all, preparation, within the framework of our course, it is preparation for decision-making.

49:19.000 --> 49:31.000
To do this, you need to carry out an intensive search for new ideas, including using the methods that we discussed,

49:32.000 --> 49:42.000
which correspond to the desired goals and openly assess possible options.

49:43.000 --> 49:57.000
It is imperative to analyze the unrealistic, lost opportunities in order to make decisions more effective, more qualitative in the future.

49:57.000 --> 50:17.000
And it is very important not to give chances to those forces that can block your actions to make a decision at the stage of either its preparation or implementation.

50:17.000 --> 50:37.000
The second recommendation of Pol.nat, which absolutely agrees with all theorists and practitioners, is that you need to be focused on the problem.

50:37.000 --> 50:52.000
You do not need to implement the first idea that came to mind, accompanying it with intensive and large-scale efforts to manipulate the facts.

50:52.000 --> 51:09.000
That is, you do not need to create a visibility of the gigantic work carried out, but, in fact, to carry out a lot of useless, unnecessary work.

51:09.000 --> 51:24.000
You need to use an approach that involves a thorough analysis of the collected information and which will lead to the best results.

51:24.000 --> 51:40.000
And it is very important to plan enough time for the development of an effective solution that is aimed at solving the problem.

51:40.000 --> 51:55.000
Since, having made a decision in a hurry, without allocating time and other resources, you can then pay a much higher price for eliminating problems.

51:55.000 --> 52:10.000
The third recommendation of Pol.nat says that you need to spend resources reasonably. And the reasonableness will be as follows.

52:10.000 --> 52:24.000
You need to spend more time and money on making a decision at the beginning, that is, at the stage of its preparation, and not on eliminating problems in the future.

52:24.000 --> 52:39.000
Provide resources for the search for better alternatives and coordination of different points of view.

52:39.000 --> 52:57.000
Make investments, that is, a certain kind of investment in financial and human resources, in the analysis of the problem, in the search for all viable alternatives.

52:57.000 --> 53:05.000
And develop solutions that meet the needs of all interested parties.

53:09.000 --> 53:25.000
In addition to the textbook, of course, in which it is still said in short, I highly recommend you read the book by Pol.nat, How to Avoid Traps and Errors Leading to Disaster.

53:25.000 --> 53:34.000
The book is written in English and is called Why Decisions Fail.

53:34.000 --> 53:49.000
The next author of the generalization of typical errors, or rather authors, is John Hammond, Ralph Kinney and Howard Raiff.

53:49.000 --> 54:02.000
They studied 8 psychological errors, in which managers or just people are most often caught when making decisions.

54:02.000 --> 54:20.000
These errors, they called themselves e-correction, status quo, an attempt to justify the previous decision, a trap of the desired and real, incorrect wording, over-insurance and memory permanence.

54:20.000 --> 54:33.000
And the trap of e-correction makes it too important to give the original information.

54:33.000 --> 54:43.000
That is, we, as they say, are so hooked on what we once heard or saw.

54:43.000 --> 55:05.000
This feature of human thinking, the work of the human brain can be used even to push you to the wrong decision,

55:05.000 --> 55:14.000
if there are forces in this interested and which pursue their hidden goals.

55:14.000 --> 55:20.000
The next trap is called the desire to maintain the status quo.

55:20.000 --> 55:27.000
That is, we all want everything to stay as it is.

55:27.000 --> 55:37.000
And this makes us adhere to the current state of things, even if there is a better alternative choice.

55:37.000 --> 55:47.000
What are irreversible costs that push us to repeat past mistakes?

55:48.000 --> 56:00.000
If we have already made a decision that was not very successful, but at the same time we have spent a certain amount of resources,

56:00.000 --> 56:08.000
then a person, purely psychologically, strives to protect himself and his decision.

56:08.000 --> 56:23.000
He tries to do the same again and again and prove that the situation, let's say, did not go as planned, but the decision was actually correct, and so on.

56:23.000 --> 56:29.000
Very often we take what is desirable for what is real, and we begin to...

56:29.000 --> 56:44.000
That is, we first form our opinion about how it should be, and then, with the energy worthy of the best application, we begin to look for confirmation of this opinion.

56:45.000 --> 56:53.000
In this case, we very often fall into the trap that Paul Natt was talking about.

56:53.000 --> 57:07.000
We begin to selectively approach the selection of information, in fact, rejecting all that information, those facts that contradict our opinion.

57:08.000 --> 57:19.000
Very often the leaders of the upper level fall into such a trap.

57:19.000 --> 57:28.000
The mistake of the wrong formulation of the problem is obviously a trap.

57:28.000 --> 57:36.000
We have discussed it many times, and I think it is absolutely transparent for understanding.

57:36.000 --> 57:43.000
If the problem is initially formulated incorrectly, then the decision, in fact, will be...

57:43.000 --> 57:53.000
That is, the whole process of making a decision will go down the wrong path, and it is unlikely that the decision will be effective.

57:53.000 --> 57:57.000
The next trap is self-confidence.

57:57.000 --> 58:06.000
In fact, we overestimate our own abilities to predict and give an accurate assessment.

58:06.000 --> 58:19.000
A person considers himself an expert, a person considers himself a connoisseur in this field, and is too dependent on his judgments.

58:19.000 --> 58:29.000
The other side and another trap is the desire to overestimate yourself.

58:29.000 --> 58:37.000
On the contrary, a person becomes overly careful when predicting unlikely events.

58:37.000 --> 58:50.000
This trap is very well connected with the topic we discussed with Matias Nölke and Paul Hnat.

58:50.000 --> 58:57.000
There is another trap that John Hammond talks about.

58:57.000 --> 59:08.000
It is the permanence of memory, which makes us attach too much importance to the tragic events of the past.

59:08.000 --> 59:15.000
As a simple example, John Hammond and the authors give such an example.

59:15.000 --> 59:31.000
If you drive a car, you can say with 99% certainty that after a while you will drive much more carefully.

59:31.000 --> 59:56.000
The last set of mistakes I would like to talk about is the generalization of my experience and theoretical knowledge

59:56.000 --> 01:00:02.000
that I have gained during my own work.

01:00:02.000 --> 01:00:07.000
These are mistakes related to the study.

01:00:07.000 --> 01:00:16.000
One way or another, they will be in conflict with what we have just discussed.

01:00:16.000 --> 01:00:19.000
Nevertheless, let's list them.

01:00:20.000 --> 01:00:29.000
1. The purpose of the study is unclear or the true purpose is not brought to the knowledge of the performers.

01:00:29.000 --> 01:00:38.000
The first mistake related to conducting scientific research appears at the very beginning

01:00:38.000 --> 01:00:45.000
and is related to the fact that at the beginning of the study the purpose may not be clear.

01:00:46.000 --> 01:00:56.000
Or, which is also quite often the case, the true purpose is not brought to the knowledge of the performers.

01:00:56.000 --> 01:01:09.000
In this case, it is very difficult for the performers to choose the correct methodology and collect relevant information.

01:01:09.000 --> 01:01:16.000
2. The second mistake has already been discussed with you many times.

01:01:16.000 --> 01:01:27.000
It is an incorrectly formulated problem, and therefore the purpose of the study and the whole plan of conducting the study.

01:01:28.000 --> 01:01:38.000
3. The next mistake is related to the fact that the wrong strategy and methodology of conducting the study are chosen,

01:01:38.000 --> 01:01:44.000
which does not allow to get reliable and reliable information.

01:01:45.000 --> 01:01:56.000
4. The next mistake is also very common and is present in all authors we have discussed.

01:01:56.000 --> 01:02:05.000
It is that the new information is selected in accordance with the already formed preferences.

01:02:05.000 --> 01:02:11.000
That is, we are talking about the pre-conception in the collection of information.

01:02:11.000 --> 01:02:27.000
5. Another mistake is related to the fact that the information collection is carried out for so long that the decision, in fact, loses relevance.

01:02:27.000 --> 01:02:45.000
This can be evidenced by the fact that a person does not want to make a decision, and also by the fact that he simply creates a visibility of conducting the study, and in fact this does not happen.

01:02:45.000 --> 01:02:55.000
But maybe this is a conscientious collection of a huge amount of information, and, in general, everything happens as we said.

01:02:55.000 --> 01:03:13.000
If the information is collected reliably and reliably, then it does not mean that further mistakes are excluded.

01:03:13.000 --> 01:03:33.000
Without preconceptions, the collected information can already be analyzed, generalized and presented in the interests of individual persons or groups.

01:03:33.000 --> 01:03:48.000
Moreover, two situations are possible here. When a person who is collecting information in advance knows the preferences of the problem owner,

01:03:48.000 --> 01:04:04.000
or he assumes that it will be well received by those who are provided with this information.

01:04:04.000 --> 01:04:20.000
In any case, this distorts the real picture of the situation and can lead to an ineffective decision and lead the person making the decision to delusion.

01:04:20.000 --> 01:04:40.000
The next mistake is due to the fact that the information collection is very fast, time is very saved and all other resources, and this leads to superficial analysis and unreliable conclusions.

01:04:40.000 --> 01:04:50.000
The next mistake, which has already sounded in several other forms, is as follows.

01:04:50.000 --> 01:05:10.000
The next mistake, which has already sounded in several other forms, is as follows.

01:05:10.000 --> 01:05:27.000
The next mistake, and this was also noted by Paul Natt, is that the research can be carried out without compliance with the norms of corporate and general human ethics,

01:05:27.000 --> 01:05:37.000
which can lead to the violation of the rights of individual members of the collective and to the emergence of conflicts in this collective.

01:05:37.000 --> 01:05:57.000
Moreover, even the problem of putting or not putting research participants in the public knowledge of what is being studied is related to compliance with the norms of corporate and other ethics.

01:05:57.000 --> 01:06:09.000
This is a question of ethics, which we discussed in great detail in the course of the research method.

01:06:09.000 --> 01:06:32.000
And the last mistake, which has already become a cliché in reviews of dissertations, reports, and so on, is that the conclusions do not correspond to the results of the research.

01:06:32.000 --> 01:06:55.000
This is a very common mistake, which can be associated with the fact that a person, when describing the results of the research or dissertation in his report,

01:06:56.000 --> 01:07:13.000
keeps something else in mind, and in fact, the conclusion of the work is based not only on what is available for the reader in the report or the reader in the dissertation,

01:07:13.000 --> 01:07:27.000
but also on what a person had in his mind. In this case, the work can be recognized as ineffective,

01:07:27.000 --> 01:07:47.000
and the leader, having read such a report, will be forced to ask a large number of additional questions to understand why this conclusion was obtained.

01:07:47.000 --> 01:08:02.000
Well, to conclude the discussion on mistakes, we will make a few sentences of conclusions.

01:08:02.000 --> 01:08:23.000
The first is that mistakes, in fact, are not to be feared. On the one hand, you can protect yourself from mistakes and traps, and the best protection is knowledge.

01:08:24.000 --> 01:08:43.000
That is, what we have discussed now, what you can read in addition, will allow you to learn to recognize these traps and avoid them, and, accordingly, will give you more confidence in making decisions.

01:08:43.000 --> 01:08:58.000
But at the same time, you need to learn on your own, to be able to learn from your mistakes. After all, every unsuccessful attempt gives new knowledge and new information.

01:08:58.000 --> 01:09:25.000
If the decision was made based on well-selected, analyzed information, that is, it was worked out, then nothing will prevent you from making an analysis of what was done in order to avoid it later.

01:09:25.000 --> 01:09:41.000
In the practice of business, in many successful companies, it is even customary to study mistakes.

01:09:41.000 --> 01:09:59.000
There, employees are not punished for their mistakes, because it allows you to find and determine the weak points in order to do your job better in the future.

01:09:59.000 --> 01:10:27.000
The following recommendation says that you need to openly admit your mistakes. You know, there is such a thing as a wish. If you laugh at yourself, others will not laugh at you anymore. Not interesting.

01:10:27.000 --> 01:10:49.000
In the same way, if you try to hide all the time that you made a mistake, sooner or later they will find out about it, they will talk behind your back, so it is better to openly admit your mistake and maybe even ask for advice on how to avoid it in the future.

01:10:49.000 --> 01:11:08.000
If you are a boss, then Robert Townsend says that you do not need to blame your colleagues for mistakes and gives such a phrase as an example.

01:11:08.000 --> 01:11:31.000
If you slap your child every time he falls, he will never like to walk. Therefore, in order for your subordinates to conduct qualitative research, prepare effective solutions for you and make effective management decisions themselves,

01:11:31.000 --> 01:11:39.000
they must be sure that they will not be fired for making a mistake.

01:12:02.000 --> 01:12:13.000
If you will fix the main goals and tasks of the project, as well as the criteria in accordance with which the decision can be made or rejected.

01:12:13.000 --> 01:12:32.000
It is also important to be responsible for the collection and preparation of information for making a decision and to conduct a planned work with information, focusing on the planned results.

01:12:32.000 --> 01:12:53.000
It is also important to plan the work on the collection and analysis of information on the results and deadlines of the study, generalization, preparation of prototypes, and so on.

01:12:53.000 --> 01:12:57.000
That is, the work must be conducted in a planned manner.

01:12:57.000 --> 01:13:25.000
And the last thing we just discussed. The correctness of the management decision is guaranteed. Not 100%, of course, but nevertheless, if you learn to either avoid mistakes or traps or make correct conclusions from a failed experience.

